ODE VIII

‘UNDER other circumstances, Censorinus, I would send my friends bronzes and pictures‚ and you should have the best of them. As it is I have none to give, and you would not care for them. Verse you will value and verse I can give; and hear now the value 1 set on the gift. Statues and inscriptions, the great feats of the Punic wars, do not throw such lustre on generals like the Scipios, as do the verses of Ennius. Would father Romulus nave lived without a grateful posterity to tell of him? Would Aeacus have won the happy islands but for Pindar's Muse? The Muse gives immortality, and instals her favourites in a place in heaven; witness HerculeS, the Tyndaridae, Bacchus himself!

C. Marcius Censorinus was consul in B.C. 8, and died, amid general regret, A. D. 2. Vell. Paterculus calls him ⁴ vir demerendis hominibus natus.’
